title: Single axle semi trailer dolly Tamiya 1/14 compatible

description.text:
A Minimalist Single Axle Trailer Dolly

Very basic, frame rails, tongue, fifth wheel plate and a rear bumper. Nothing extra here, but still some decent scale detail in the fifth wheel plate and frame rails that are strong enough even in PLA.

Tamiya hardware

This design has integrated mounting holes to use a single axle Tamiya suspension setup. You will need some spacers from the Tamiya kit (I've attached instructions illustrating those as well as the plastic adapters to put a single axle in the middle o the leaf spring (also added photos for that). These are on the "C" tree for most Tamiya trucks I think. There are options on thingiverse for printing some of these parts as well. The other parts that come from Tamiya kits are the fifth wheel itself, associated mounting hardware and the release mechanism. You can also obtain the rectangle taillight lenses from the flatbed kit and mudflaps or make your own.

Additional hardware needed

The front tongue is held on by 4mm battery bullet connectors and you'll need a few extra 3mm screws (the same as used in all Tamiya kits) to put the rest of it together. The rear bumper and the top plate use wood style threads and thread right into the rails. All other fasteners have a recessed hole for a flanged lock nut also used in Tamiya kits. A few spacers for the leaf spring to frame rail mount are included to print.

The tongue

The tongue is currently designed to leverage the rc4wd pintle hook mount. Its not the cheapest, but is pretty good looking and I think accurate for the style used in the US. The tongue is a fixed position and does not hinge from the frame rails.

With that said, its fairly trivial to adapt the design to a different type of mount like a rod end. If you want a specific type of mount, post in the comments and I'll do my best to provide it and add it to the make, or you can load up that .stl into tinkercad and make it for yourself.

Feedback is welcome, happy making!

These piles invariably end up getting flicked around and mixed with other piles. It can also be hard to pick up the resources off of the board out of the shifting pile. The bottoms of the bowls are mostly flattened to avoid tipping. If printed in grey, the chipped stone design makes the presence of the bowls pleasantly thematic. This is a tried and tested Tiny Whoov frame I designed (For those who do not know, a tiny whoov or whoover is a small hovercraft made from quadcotper parts).

This design is intended to be used in combination with a piece of foam board to allow for a very lightweight frame but also easy and accurate assembly. The 3D printed main plate combined with the motor towers allows for a very rigid and strong frame that can take hit after hit. In addition, this design can be used universally with different whoov shapes and sizes. It is, however, intended to be used with inductrix sized flight controllers with the provided holes. Other flight controllers can be used but may not be able to use the holes in the design. All motor mounting points are designed to fit 6mm motors and lager motors will not fit in this revision of the frame. If there is demand, I will add a 7mm motor variant.

I have also included the STL for a propeller guard that is intended to fit onto a motor. This will help reduce propeller strikes with nearby objects. I am not currently using this part because my current whoov's body is large enough to hit an object before a propeller can. This part should be printed in a harder filament because squishy filaments will squish upon impact and the propeller may still hit the object.

To attach the motor towers you can use acetone welding (For PLA), superglue, or pretty much any other bonding technique that works with your filament. I used superglue combined with my PLA print.

The motors on my Whoov do get hot, and so I decided to reinforce my motor mounts for the lifting motors with zip ties as shown in the picture.

Feedback is welcome!

description.text:
This is my first time attempt to making anything close to a pod. Wound up being more of a half shell than a pod. Couple of years ago, a fellow quad builder set out to make pods and ascertained that it couldn't be done in TinkerCAD. A month ago, after not having flown my Mikro in a year, I decided to force myself to replace the broken cam/vtx, find better props and get this cute lil bugger tuned and flying like a real quad. But then, the replacement cam/vtx had its antenna off to the side which made it impossible to conform to the Mikro's original top plate.
That set me off to designing a top plate alternative which is here among my designs. It's PLA based and pretty strong. One thing accomplished plants another seed, and this one triggered me into seeing if I can actually make TinkerCad conform to my mind's idea for a pod. It was a learning experience for sure. Probably not the way to go in the long run as you'll probably want to learn how to use the real CAD tools. But, at least you now know what I know, and that it is possible to do in TinkerCad.

I'm already "tinkering" around with a newer design from scratch. Meanwhile, I hope you enjoy this one. It is TPU based, meaning, it will not be strong if you print in PLA. Trust me. Tried that just to see, and decided TPU is the appropriate material.

The only thing about this design that I'm not totally happy with is easy access to the VTX band/channel buttons from the top. There is none. You have to use a thin poker and go in from the side. The last other thing is, there isn't in my opinion, total protection for your cam. Which is why I set off to design another one. If you're a beginner just learning to fly, you probably want to stick with the original top plate as much as possible to protect your FPV gear or, find a better half shell/pod.

Cheers, and happy flying

description.text:
Stone age is an excellent game and an excellent introduction into the worker placement genre. Unfortunately, it relies on the all too familiar ziplock organization system. It also requires too much sorting and division during setup. This is too good a game to require so much fiddling and sorting before getting into it. Fortunately, you won't have to do this for long. Here's what you can find inside:
Hut Tray - This tray separates the huts into four sections making setup simple. If you shuffle these after every game, the next time you bring it out, setup can be as easy as pushing out the required number of sections and placing them in their appropriate places on the board.
Card Tray - This tray comes in three modes, not including its completely enclosed card holder state. These modes can be mixed or matched by removing the slide in lids, as you see fit.
Tool Tray - This tray was intended to remove the need for sorting the tiles by 1/2 and 3/4 before play. The open bottoms make removal easy
Meeple Tray - This tray has a slide on lid that can be pulled back just enough to expose one color of meeples and markers, they can then be dumped out and handed to each player in turn.

These few items make setup and put away a breeze, and are all designed to use a minimal amount of material while remaining durable and rigid. You may want to check out these helpful bowls, as well. They make managing and using resources during gameplay a cinch. Enjoy!

title: E012 Eachine drone storage box - LASER cut

description.text:
So, this is simply a LASER cut-able storage box for your Eachine E012 drone.

You can store the drone, remote, spare (Li) batteries, spare propellers and charger cable, all in one place so they don't migrate.

Of the two lower horizontal pieces inside the box, one is larger than the other - test before gluing!

The lid is a little tricky to place/remove until you play with it a few times, but I wanted to be able to cut and glue a box with effectively no moving parts (no screws, no hinges that stick out, no sliding mechanisms with springs, etc.).

Files are in .AI format, and have layers. I use Coreldraw with LASERDRAW plugin, so I need to (vector) engrave the 'mark' layer first, then cut the 'cut' layer afterward. Organise your own cutting/engraving order to taste.

The part 1&2 .AI files are for cutting on a K40 laser (300x200mm limits). If you have a bigger bed, grab the 'full' .AI and cut it in one hit.
My K40 engraves nicely at 20mm/s with around 4mA tube current. For cutting, I run somewhere around 6-7mm/s at 15mA. YMMV as I only use a basic air assist, but have excellent extraction.

Material I used was 3mm MDF, but acrylic or any other 3mm material should be alright. Be aware that the living latch (needed to open the box) was tweaked for MDF/wood. you may need to make a new/different pattern to support acrylic.

The marks in the base piece are purely to align the drone feet holders.
The internal spacers, in addition to partitioning the box for convenient storage, also allow the remote to sit ABOVE the drone, and cannot crush it (a stock version anyway).

Good luck, and hopefully it's useful!

description.text:
I love my keyboard.io Model 01 keyboard. Except I don't particularly love the "spider" stands that came with it - they lift the keyboard up a bit too high and are generally hard to adjust to fit to the ideal tilt for my wrists.

So I made these minimal wedges that fit under the keyboard as a replacement, using the thumbscrews that came with the keyboard and a little bit of hot glue.

The design is customizable with the amount of tilt; the default value of 15 matches the included spider stands. In theory this should also be usable with the tented center support, should you want to use that, although it would be better to simply put a 2cm-tall block of wood + rubber feet under it (perhaps attaching that to the center bar with hot glue).

This file only generates a single wedge, in case you want them to tent differently for some reason. You'll need to print one for each keyboard half. I am able to fit both wedges within a single print on my MakerBot Replicator Dual but your mileage may vary.

Hot glue is versatile

Use some hot glue to make some little rubber feet for it. I recommend putting a few thin lines on the backside to prevent it from spinning around (especially near the thru-hole for the thumbscrew) and some larger dollops on the three feet; these will be your actual support for the keyboard.

Leveling the feet can be a bit tricky. One way that works well is to use the heated tip of the glue gun to reshape whichever foot sticks out the most. Another approach is to attach the feet to the keyboard before adding the feet, then when it's mostly cooled down but still a bit soft, put the keyboard right-side up atop some thin paper (such as newsprint) and press it down to shape the feet. Then you can carefully peel the paper away from the glue and hopefully it's all shaped right!

Using the glue gun to reshape the foot

I wanted to add LEDs to BB-8 to match my BB-9E design, so I reworked wkarraker's excellent BB-8's dome/head to include ports for LEDs.

The LEDs are powered by three LR44 button batteries. I used a sparre SPDT micro slide switch I had to turn the LEDs on or off. Depending on the switch you use, you might have to modify the bottom and bottom ring. I soldered a 200 ohm resistor to the positive legs of the red and blue LEDs and a 120 ohm resistor on the white LED. The LEDs were then wired in parrallel to the switch and batteries.

description.text:
So here it is

Filterholder for the Nikon 14-24 2.8

(and as far as I know, the first free one)


I recently found again my love for photography and wanted do more landscape and architecture. So after some time and thought (and money!!!) I got myself the famous Nikon 14-24 2.8, great lens, but unfortunately it does not take normal filters. Even the "not so normal" cokin filters (had some 100x100) won't fit.

The cheapest single Filterplate costs about 115€ but that is without any holder to mount it to the lens. Those again cost from 150-500€. There is even a 3D-Printed one wich is nice but to be honest.... 3D-Printing (and therefor 3D-Printed Parts) for me has a kind of "communitiy" feel to it so if you design something great for 3D-Printing I think you should share it with others (still its ok and understandable to also sell finished parts but you should share the files!).

So long story short I, of course made my own one! It needed quite some thought to get the right dimensionslos so that nothing "blocks" the picture at 14mm (about 114° angle!!!).

Key features:

  • No vignetting
  • Light: at least lighter than the ones made out of metal
  • Easy to print: only minimal supported areas needed
  • almost No manual rework: ok don't nail me down on this, I sanded the inner diameter to get a better surface for the foam rubber (the inserts in the pictures are a prototype so those are heavily sanded)
  • Removable holder inserts: you can remove the bottom ones to use for instance a gradual ND filter
  • Interchangeable holder inserts: there will be an additional version for 2 stacked filters

==================================================================

What you will need:

  • 3D-Printer: haha... I know
  • 1 Main Part
  • 3 Inserts L
  • 3 Inserts R
  • 1,8-2mm thick self sticking foam rubber
  • 6pcs 1,5x14mm cylinder pin
  • some sandpaper

==================================================================


Hope everyone likes the part and has a great time shooting photos with it ;-)






Just two more things I have to say:

  1. I am not to hold responsible for anyone scratching the outside of his lens or cracking a filter (becaus it drops out or smth.). The holder works great for me but your results may vary (Printer settings, material,....)
  2. Please don't sell it. Since the next option is over 100€ someone might be tempted to sell some for money. Material cost plus 4 or 5 beers ;-) is fine but I would like that no one is "making money" out of it.

title: Google Home Mini Plug Mount - UK

description.text:
The Google Home Mini is a great addition to the kitchen - step by step recipes, weight conversions, music and the most awesome kitchen timer ever. But how to mount it out of the way and deal with that long cable? I saw a mount on ebay that was ideal but realised it was basically a customised rip off of maxr525's fantastic mount without any attribution. I've searched high and low for the design but came up with nothing.

So, for the benefit of those who like the design, I've produced my own take on it, giving maxr525 the kudos deserved.

maxr525's mount is (in my view) the most elegant mount design for the mini on Thingiverse. I have simply added a double-walled, slotted cylinder to the rear. The inner cylinder slips over the power plug supplied with the mini. The gap between the inner and outer cylinder allows you to coil the vast majority of the power cable within the walls so the cable remains hidden.

I don't know if the PSU sizes vary between regions, so it may well be standard and fit on other plugs.

Prints without supports (in PLA) if you have decent hot-end cooling.

description.text:
From Wikipedia:

The Miura fold (ミウラ折り Miura-ori) is a method of folding a flat surface such as a sheet of paper into a smaller area. The fold is named for its inventor, Japanese astrophysicist Koryo Miura.

The crease patterns of the Miura fold form a tessellation of the surface by parallelograms. In one direction, the creases lie along straight lines, with each parallelogram forming the mirror reflection of its neighbor across each crease. In the other direction, the creases zigzag, and each parallelogram is the translation of its neighbor across the crease. Each of the zigzag paths of creases consists solely of mountain folds or of valley folds, with mountains alternating with valleys from one zigzag path to the next. Each of the straight paths of creases alternates between mountain and valley folds.

The Miura fold is a form of rigid origami, meaning that the fold can be carried out by a continuous motion in which, at each step, each parallelogram is completely flat. This property allows it to be used to fold surfaces made of rigid materials. For instance, large solar panel arrays for space satellites in the Japanese space program have been Miura folded before launch and then spread out in space. A folded Miura fold can be packed into a compact shape, its thickness reflecting only the thickness of the folded material. Folded material can be unpacked in one motion by pulling on its opposite ends, and likewise folded by pushing the two ends together. In the solar array application, this property reduces the number of motors required to unfold this shape, reducing weight and complexity.

Evolve Today with Plasmids!

This is a plasmid from bioshock powered power an Adafruit Feather nRF52 Bluefruite LE.

I remodeled the parts from the separated plasmid pieces of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1916218 in fusion 360 so i can adjust them to hold electronics.

BOM:

Adafruit Feather nRF52 Bluefruit LE (https://www.adafruit.com/product/3406)
On-Off Power Button (https://www.adafruit.com/product/1683)

Notes:

Base, Top, and Center Core require supports. Remove supports for the threads in the Top part if you can. Do not use supports for the Cap, the threads will be harder to get working. Requires 4x of Arm Part

Parts printed in eSun PLA+ @215 C Hot end, 50mm/s, 70 C Heated bed, 20% infil
Core printed in Colorfabb XT Clear @ 245 C Hot end, 50mm/s, 70 C Heated Bed, 80% infil

Core

Sand core surface with 220 grit Sandpaper to diffuse Neopixel light.

Assembly

1) Wire PWR, Data IN, and GND to Neo Pixel Ring

2) Feed wires into Core Part to seat the Ring

  • The core has 4 slots built into the bottom, feed wire from outside in to seat the ring properly (See Image Below)

3) Seat battery in Base part

  • There is small indent for wires

4) Attach Base part to Core part through twist mechanism

  • Battery wires should fit through slot
  • Some sanding may be required to get the twist to work, it is really snug depending on printer tolerance.
  • See image below for reference.

5) Place Center Core part into the assembly, feeding only the 3 Neopixel wires through the center (See Image for reference)

6) Add wire to ON/OFF switch and place into Top part. (Image for reference)

  • This is a snug fit so it will take some effort to set.
  • Make sure the Cap part and Top part thread well before adding the switch. It will be difficult to remove the switch after placing.
  • You can use shrink wrap to secure solder points for switch wires but it may get stuck in slot so be careful.

7) Wire everything to Adafruit Feather (See Pin Wiring Below)

8) Recommended: Test code and wiring at this point to make sure it all works. Good Idea to charge the battery as well.

9) Shove wires and Feather into center core.

  • This will be annoying but everything will fit.
  • Make sure battery port is exposed through holes on side of the Center Core Part

10) Plug Battery into feather. (Tricky to due because of space but possible)

11) Shove ON/OFF Wires into Center Core and mate Top with Core.

12) Add Arms to secure assembly closed

13) Thread Cap on to Top

14) Enjoy!

Wiring

NeoPixel Ring

  • Power -> 3V
  • Data in -> Pin 30
  • GND -> GND

ON/OFF Switch
One side to EN pin, one side to GND. This will allow charging while the 3V regulator is turned off.

Code

Code provided works with Adafruit Bluefruit LE app on Andriod and iOS with Controller Mode.

Button 1 sets color to red
Button 2 sets color to blue
Button 3 sets color to yellow
Button 4 turns Neopixels off
Button 5 (up arrow) shows random colors to simulate the Unstable teleport plasmid from Bioshock 2

This Thing is a spool hub designed for use on 5/16" (8mm) threaded rod. It is slotted to prevent the user from having to completely remove the nuts to change spools. It was originally designed for use with 2ROBOTGUY's "SIMPLE SPOOL HOLDER FOR MENDEL" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7982) but I'm sure it would work with other designs also. Update:
I fixed the scale problem and also added an unslotted version. A slotted hub is really only necessary on one side. You could even lock the unslotted hub in place with a washer and nuts on the inside for simpler spool changes.

Required Items:
2 - Spool Hubs
2 - 608 Bearings
2 - Flat Washer (to match your threaded rod)
4 - Nuts (to match your threaded rod) Initial Assembly:
Using a 1/2 drill bit, drill out the support from the back side of the hub. On each side of the spool install the following components in this order: hub, bearing, washer, nut, nut. The bearing should be a slip fit into the hub. There is no need to tighten the nuts against the bearings/hubs. Just lightly snug and lock in place with the other nut. Changing Spools:
Just loosen the nuts on one side of the spool enough to remove the bearing from the hub. Using the slot remove the hub from the threaded rod. Slide the spool off.

This 'thing' supersedes version 1. V2 is superior to v1 because:
  • it is simpler (less plastic), and comes as a single piece (no welding required).
  • the base in v1 is too thin (2mm) - it buckled in the heat / sun inside my car. The base in v2 is 6mm-thick.
  • the flanges on the base of v1 (designed to slot into the cup-holder) sometimes failed to work properly when cornering (phone + holder ended up on the floor of the car).

I felt it made sense to print the phone-holder part, but leave the cup-holder part to you. My personal cup-holder attachment consists of a 'puck' made out of disks of corrugated cardboard. The puck is laced to the 'thing' with string. The puck fits snugly into my non-circular cup-holder, and is much more secure than v1. Another method of attachment could be a cross-bar (e.g. chop-stick) under the cup-holder + zip-lock ties through the slots provided. This is an original 3d file representing an 28mm scale model of the "Odessa Tank", built in the early days of the Soviet Union's Great Patriotic War. Here is a good review of the tank's origin:

This is a 28mm model of a WW2 Soviet Anti Tank dog. If you are not familiar with the Red Army's use of this weapon, here is a good overview:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-tank_dog
This model can be used with the Bolt Action gaming system. I play a Soviet Army in the game, and the Red Army has a dearth of anti-tank options (no panzer-shreks, PIATS, bazookas, etc, and only limited #s of captured panzerfausts later in the war), but one asset is the anti-tank dog. The problem is Warlord Games sells them as a pack of two dogs and two "handlers"; the handlers have nothing to distinguish themselves from any other Soviet infantry, so you end up paying $15 (Cdn.) for two dogs... I thought by creating a 3d option, I could expand my dog team.
I have not printed something so small before, and 3D printing at home has limitations. I started with a very large file (attributed) and downsized it; thickened the torso and legs, and created the "bomb pack". After several test prints, you see what I arrived at. I should look better once I paint it; I did a photo of it beside the Warlord dog model.
When printing, as always, be very careful removing supports - it is tricky as the supports are under the torso and between the legs.
I put it on a 25mm base; in the photo my base sits a little higher as I glue a 1" metal washer under all my bases, as I used a magnetized storage system.

A three-dimensional shape that looks like a soccer ball and can be made as big as a soccer ball. The design is fully parametric so can be printed at any size. If you want, you can replace one or more of the hexagons with other printed parts that have the hinges in the same position and create more things.

You need twenty hexagons to print the ball, 10 type A and 10 type B. They differ in the type of hinges they have on three sides. Type A has two inner hinges and one outer and type B the opposite. Each STL file contains one A and one B.  
You'll also need filament to use as the hinge pin. I use glow-in-the-dark because it's about the right size, often needing to sand it down a little. I recommend printing one pair of parts and then making sure you are happy with the inner diameter of the hinge before going on.  
The models I built (0.2 mm layers in white PLA) stay together purely by friction, but for a permanent model you'll want to add the pins.  
The large ball was about 13 hours print time on a Replicator 1 and weighed about 200g. The small one took much less since I could get lots of parts on the plate at once.  
Once printed, lay the parts out in the way I show in the photos, paying careful attention to which hinge is which, then mate the parts. Finally roll up into a ball and add the pins.  
To build from SCAD, put all the files in the same folder, then open the hex.scad file. It may take a minute or two to open since it is slow to render. Edit the parameters at the bottom to change the dimensions. You will want to keep the hinge diameter the same as the thickness of the piece.  
The SCAD files allow you to vary the number of sides on the part too, but as written will take some extra coding to vary the number of hinges from three.

description.text:
This mechanism, based on the Win-Bin Shieh 8 bar linkage, is essentially a Chebyshev Lambda or plantigrade mechanism, inverted then inverted again with a pantograph. The Lambda is already known to have a smooth and flat motion, but located above the linkage. So here the Lambda is rotated upside down, then to invert the motion, a pantograph is used (here 2 pantographs for front and back leg). The pantograph could also produce larger scaled motion but here I used 1:1 scale. The ski which connects the front and back leg provides wide ground contact area.

Video: https://youtu.be/AfgMdyHlt1A

I surely used a lot of screws, all M3 with length 6 mm, 10 mm, and 15 mm. For the long axles I used 3 mm iron wire. There are 2.8mm diameter holes, which need to be tapped for M3 screw, and 3.2mm holes, which might need to be drilled clean.

The servo horn need to be drilled 3 mm diameter at position 1 cm from the center. 2 screws fasten the horn to the crank1 part. The servo mounting holes are designed slightly wider than the real size, this is for compensating shrinkage.

This is a 28mm model of the Spanish Civil War Constructora Field Car #3. The background of the vehicle is covered in this link:
http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/spain/constructora-field/
I started with Jarlang's excellent model of the Constructora #2, and upscaled it to 28mm. I created the new front end to represent the different design on Car #3, as well as making the wheels separate (they fit into recesses under the hull) and adding details- pistol ports, engine access panels, vision slits and a back door. This vehicle was used as an APC, and carries 9 men, so its value in a Bolt Action game is considerable; with a 7+ armour rating, in a properly historical force mix, it provides some good opportunities.
As noted in the link, there were at least nine of these cars crafted by the Loyalists in Barcelona; note the ventilation Tubes on this model are set into the top of the hull; and don't protrude as much as the earlier models - each car has differences, and I did this one up as best I could from both english and spanish language sources. As they were built on the fly, there are few records post-SCW recounting their manufacture.
If using them when gaming the Spanish Civil War, please don't be limited to using it as a Loyalist AFV; both sides in the conflict captured their opponent's AFVs and used them against their former owner.

description.text: Created in Solidworks
pieces taken apart

Gearbugs are toys built from gears. Gearbug #2 a planetary gear system built to be turned by hand. Oddly addicting to sit and turn. Requires a single M3x12 bolt and nut. You can see what it looks like in action here: http://authenticinvention.com/images/gearbug/GearBug2sm.gif

• Cut out all the parts with a laser cutter from 1/8th inch MDF or plywood. The file is in Inkscape format. I cut black first, then blue then red.
  • Glue the big ring to the back. Make sure to line it up exactly.
  • Using the bolt as a giude, glue the sun gear to the handle. Make sure the radial holes line up.
  • wait for the wood glue to dry. You don't want to glue the plaentary gears to anything by mistake.
  • Put the bolt up through the bottom.
  • Line up the three planet gears around the outside spaced evenly.
  • gently lower the handle and sun into the middle.
  • put some thread locking compound on a nut and thread it on. It need to be flush with the top of the screw. Not too tight, not too loose.
  • wipe off excess locking compound and let the glue dry before turning the handle.

I was playing with the idea of making a DiY power wheels type toy for my son. and decided to first attempt at a solid rear axle with diff.

deciding at this scale it would be cool to make a semi realistic version.

it's designed with a few changes.. For starters the vast majority of it was assembled with 5/8 bolts and nuts from a hardware store.

the outputs from the center diff are 1" PVC pipe. and I used a threaded rod to a long bolt for the drive output. (the bolt was glued into the corresponding diff gears) At tje ends I glued skateboard bearings in.

The diff gears for the outputs AND the diff, all were designed to run on 17x30x7mm ball bearings (I ordered mine intended for a HPI Baha 1/5 rc truck off amazon)

The entire axle was printed in ABS. and many parts were smoothed with acetone and/or bonded using a combination of screws, glue, and acetone bonding.

the input for the drive gear needs a threaded rod. I don't have a solid solution for this. I used a hollow rod, some washers, a lot of glue, and a threaded rod to drive it. it's not the best solution!

I have not finished my own print quite yet. so I don't have all the answers or details. it's very much a DIY project!

comments.text:
How old is your son? I have a 6 year old that I was thinking of modifying his power wheels 4 wheeler into something cooler.
I think it would be pretty awesome to build something with realistic differentials and if you went with a tubular frame you could probably get away with minimal welding and it would be extremely adjustable which would also mean very forgiving if any measurements were off.
Something like a rock crawler frame but it wouldnt need to be quite as extreme.
Im still looking into tires because those crappy plastic tires just dont cut it.
One thing I have noticed for the motors is people swapping them with RC Brushless motors but continuing to use the power wheels gearboxes.
If you are interested in borrowing some of the components from a powerwheels such as the gearboxes and electronics then Id recommend the same 4 wheeler I have. I think they can be purchased for around $200 from Walmart but if you could find one used with dead batteries or something I bet it could be had for around $50.

description.text:
This is a self-contained 3D printable rover track that can be reused on your projects.

Many times I designed and downloaded already designed rovers to be 3D printed. Usually there is no isolation between the rover tracks and the rest of the body. This leads to the need to redesign everything on any new rover you make.

The idea here is to isolate the tracks of my rovers, and create something that can be reused on many tracked robots, so you just think in the body, not the wheels.

I thought about adding also the motor controller, so you can just remove that element from your body and use that space for something else. Though it's not really needed to put the controller there if you what to use another type, or just want to place it with the rest of your electronics.

Also, as the motor controller supports two motors, you could place it in one of the tracks, and just send the power cables to the second motor. I'll show that later with pictures, so you know how to do that.

For each track you will need the following parts:
  • 1 Yellow DC Gear Motor (like this one)
  • 1 mini DC motor controller(like this)
  • Some M3 wood screws (get them here) (I find them to work perfect with 3D printed stuff. I used 10 mm ones here, but I'd recommend getting a bunch of measures, because you'll use them for sure)

The main page for this project is in here my blog, were I'll be updating and linking related projects that use this thing

You can see and download the fusion 360 design from this link. I would really appreciate if you send me a picture of your build, or mark it as "made" in this website, It is awesome to know what I did helped someone.

UPDATE 2018-03-08
You can find an example on how to add this to an already existing chassis in here

Build instructions

  • When printing the driver wheels, I would recommend to place the motor axis into the wheels hole while it is still hot. The objective is to make it fit tight without needing further work.

  • As this fits as a left or right track for a robot, there is no real left or right for this mount. That is why I named each side with A and B. Keep this naming to understand on which side of the assembly each par goes. If it has an A in the name, then it goes on the same side as the rest of the A parts, same for B.

  • Check at the list of images uploaded to this thing to get an idea of where does each part should fit

  • To link the tracks use a peace of 1.75 filament. If you leave about half millimeter extra on each side, you can melt that extra with a soldering iron, so you get a nice finish.

  • To use it in your project you can create a body that connects to the 4 screws in the inner side of the assembly, or you could just replace the wheel enclosure, and model whatever mounting points you need...

title: Re-imagined Batmobile car body in HO scale

description.text:
Inspired by, though not identical to, the Batmobile in theTelltale Batman video game. Credit goes to Matt Donie of BigBangDesignGuy.com for the renderings that inspired the look of this car.

The version with posts will fit a T-Jet chassis. The version without posts is provided in case someone wants to adapt it to some other chassis.

Car is oriented nose-up to print without added support.
Rear fin support elements can be cut off after printing, and front fins can be cut/sanded to give a swept-back look.
Shell is approximately 0.8 mm thick, made for 0.4 mm extrusion width, single perimeter, no infill, slow 16.5mm/s print speed, 0.1 mm layer height. Uncheck "Detect Thin Walls".

I use Slic3r, which is forgiving about non-manifold objects. This car will likely show as non-manifold in your slicer. There are some thin areas that will cause a slicer to leave holes if you try to make the extrusion width greater than 0.4 mm.

title: An ESP8266-based peristaltic dosing pump
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A WiFi-enabled peristaltic pump powered by a NodeMCU / ESP8266-12E microcontroller, a NEMA-17 compatible stepper motor, and an EasyDriver driver board.

This is a refinement of another user's design to be much more reliable, and was tested over many iterations until it worked flawlessly. See the remix for the original design.

Firmware provided to allow easy WiFi management and control of the device over MQTT technology as well!

A CoogleIOT based firmware is also provided which uses the AccelStepper library to provide control of the doser over MQTT available for download here:

https://github.com/ThisSmartHouse/coogle-doser

Notes:

Most parts can be printed without supports, except the rotor and the lid. It is recommended when printing the lid you flip it upside down so the bottom is facing up with supports, because even with supports the "rough" side may cause the stepper to stick.

Assembly is pretty straightforward, the parts all have slots for M3 nuts to be glued/placed and then used with bolts to secure the parts together. Each part stacks on top of the next. For the base M3 nuts are used with brass spacers to create a mount for the NodeMCU board.

For the rotor, first put a M3 nut and bolt in the shaft before assembly. Then once the stepper motor is attached insert the rotor as far down as it will go. There is a small access hole provided in the carriage so you can spin the rotor until you see the bolt and use it to tighten the rotor to the shaft of the stepper motor. Do not over tighten!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Remodelled official Bondtech BMG Creality CR-10S mount.

The issue with the standard mount is that when the end of the filament passes the sensor, it is difficult to remove the piece of filament still in the bowden tube without a lot of messing about. The extended sensor arm allows easy access to the end of the filament after it has passed the sensor switch.
It also stops the BondTech destroying the switch when using it to unload the filament.

Grab the end of the filament from the gap between the sensor and the extruder and unload by your preferred method. Much easier.

I also removed the need for supports under the sensor block during printing and increased the clearance in the filament path for the sensor switch, as the latter's lever arm can foul on the top of the chamber..

Please note: I give Full Credit to Bondtech for their original design. All I did here was a remix.

For your convenience, the reduced support version of the standard Bondtech BMG mount is also included, as is the unmodified Sensor Cap Plate.
